ARCHIVE & COMPRESS COMMANDS
1Ô∏è‚É£ tar ‚Äì Archive & Compress Files

Tar is the most used tool in Linux for backup and packaging.

Basic Commands
Command	                                              Explanation
tar -cvf backup.tar /data	                            Create archive without compression
tar -czvf backup.tar.gz /data                       	Create archive with gzip compression
tar -cjvf backup.tar.bz2 /data	                      Create archive with bzip2 compression
tar -xvf backup.tar	                                  Extract tar file
tar -xzvf backup.tar.gz -C /tmp	                      Extract to specific location
Options:

c = create

x = extract

v = verbose

f = file

z = gzip

j = bzip2

C = extract to directory

2Ô∏è‚É£ gzip / gunzip ‚Äî Compress Single Files
Command	                                              Explanation
gzip file.txt	                                        Compresses ‚Üí file.txt.gz
gunzip file.txt.gz	                                  Decompress
gzip -9 file.txt	                                    Maximum compression
3Ô∏è‚É£ zip / unzip ‚Äî Windows-Compatible Archives
Command	                                              Explanation
zip backup.zip file1 file2	                          Create zip
zip -r project.zip /project	                          Zip a folder
unzip project.zip -d /tmp	                            Extract zip file
‚úÖ 2. FILE TRANSFER COMMANDS
1Ô∏è‚É£ scp ‚Äî Secure Copy Between Systems
Basic usage:
scp file.txt user@server:/tmp


Copy folder:

scp -r /data user@server:/backup/


Copy from remote ‚Üí local:

scp user@server:/var/log/messages .

2Ô∏è‚É£ rsync ‚Äî Best tool for backup & syncing

Very commonly used in real companies.

Command	                                                        Explanation
rsync -av /data /backup	                                        Sync directories
rsync -avz /data user@server:/backup	                          Sync with compression
rsync -av --delete /data /mirror	                              Keep mirror directory

Options:

a = archive mode

v = verbose

z = compress

--delete = remove files not present in source

3Ô∏è‚É£ sftp ‚Äî Secure File Transfer Terminal
sftp user@server
put file.txt
get logs.tar.gz

üî• 3. REAL-TIME COMPANY SCENARIOS (Red Hat & DevOps)
Scenario 1: Take backup of /etc before configuration change

Command:

tar -czvf etc-backup-$(date +%F).tar.gz /etc


Why:
Before patching or upgrading services, sysadmins take backup of important configs.

Scenario 2: Transfer logs to another server for troubleshooting
scp /var/log/messages admin@10.10.1.55:/logs/server1/

Scenario 3: Sync production files to DR site using rsync
rsync -avz /var/www/html dradmin@192.168.1.20:/dr-web


Why:
Used daily in enterprise disaster recovery setups.

Scenario 4: Archive old logs monthly
tar -czvf logs-$(date +%b-%Y).tar.gz /var/log/httpd


Move it:

mv logs-*.gz /archive/

Scenario 5: Copy large files over slow network
rsync -avzP bigfile.iso user@server:/mnt/share


-P shows progress + resumes broken transfers.

‚ö†Ô∏è 4. COMMON ISSUES + SOLUTIONS
‚ùå Issue 1: Permission denied while using scp

Error:

scp file.txt user@server:/etc/
Permission denied


Solution:
Remote user doesn‚Äôt have permission.

scp file.txt user@server:/tmp
sudo mv /tmp/file.txt /etc/


Or fix permissions.

‚ùå Issue 2: tar extraction fails due to incorrect directory
tar -xzvf backup.tar.gz
tar: This does not look like a tar archive


Solution:
Check file type:

file backup.tar.gz

‚ùå Issue 3: rsync deletes important files because of --delete

Real mistake in companies

Wrong:

rsync -av --delete /source /target


If /source is empty ‚Üí /target gets deleted.

Solution:

‚úî Use --dry-run first:

rsync -av --delete --dry-run /source /target

‚ùå Issue 4: sftp connection timeout
Connection timed out


Solution:

Check firewall:

sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=ssh --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload


Check SSH:

systemctl restart sshd
